Hence,
@steps
\begin{align*}
\phi(r^is^j) \phi(r^{i'}s^{j'})^{-1} 
&= (a^ib^j)(a^{i'}b^{j'})^{-1}
&
\\
&
#nstep{= a^i b^jb^{-j'} a^{-i'}} 
&
\\
&
#nstep{= a^i b^{j - j'} a^{-i'}} 
&
\\
&
#nstep{= a^{i - i'}} 
&
#nstep{\text{ since } \ord b = 2.}
\\
&
#nstep{ = e} 
&
#nstep{\text{ since } \ord a = 3.}
\end{align*}
@endsteps
This implies that 
$\phi(r^is^j) = \phi(r^{i'}s^{j'})$.
We conclude that $\phi$ is well-defined.

