<h2>Normal Subgroups</h2>

Let $G$ be a group.

<p><blockquote><h5>Definition.</h5>
Two elements $g, h \in G$ are said to be <b>conjugate</b> if there exists $x \in G$
such that $x g x^{-1} = h$.
<p></blockquote><hr>Note that conjugacy is an equivalence relation.

For each $h \in G$, the set:
\[
h^G := \{xhx^{-1} : x \in G\}
\]
is call the <b>conjugacy class</b> of $h$.
Note that $h_1, h_2 \in G$ are conjugate if and only if $h_1^G = h_2^G$.

Since conjugacy is an equivalence relation, $G$ is a disjoint union of conjugacy classes.

Given a subgroup $H$ of $G$, and a fixed element $x \in G$,
the set:
\[
xHx^{-1} := \{xhx^{-1} : h \in G\}
\]
is also a subgroup of $G$.
We say that the subgroups $xHx^{-1}$ and $H$ are conjugate.

<p><blockquote><h5>Definition.</h5>
If $H = xHx^{-1}$ for all $x \in G$, we say that $H$ is a <b>normal subgroup.</b>
<p></blockquote><hr>If other words, $H$ is a normal subgroup of $G$ if for all $h \in H$ and $x \in G$,
we have $xhx^{-1} \in H$.

\quad\\
<b>Note.</b> $H$ is a normal subgroup if and only if for all $g \in G$, we have $gHg^{-1} \subseteq H$.

\quad\\
<b>Note.</b> If $G$ is abelian, then every subgroup of $H$ is normal.

<h2>Quotient Groups</h2>
An interesting fact is that if $H$ is a normal subgroup of a group $G$, then the collection of left cosets of $H$ in $G$
has a natural group structure.

\quad\\
<b>Notation:</b>
Let $G$ be a group, let $H$ be a normal subgroup of $G$,
we denote the collection of left cosets of $H$ in $G$ by $G/H$.

For cosets $H_1$, $H_2$ of $H$ in $G$, let:
\[
H_1 \cdot H_2 := \{h_1h_2 : h_1 \in H_1, h_2 \in H_2\}.
\]
\quad\\
<p><blockquote><h5>Claim.</h5>
$H_1 \cdot H_2$ is a left coset of $H$.
More precisely, if $H_i = g_i H$ ($i = 1, 2$),
then $H_1\cdot H_2 = g_1g_2 \in H$.
<p></blockquote><hr>
First we show that $g_1H \cdot g_2H \subseteq g_1g_2H$.
Namely, for all $h_1, h_2 \in H$, we want to show that $g_1h_1g_2h_2 = g_1g_2h$ for some $h \in H$.
Observe that:
\[
g_1h_1g_2h_2 = g_1 (g_2g_2^{-1})h_1g_2h_2 = g_1 g_2\cdot(g_2^{-1}h_1g_2)h_2
\]
Since $H$ is a normal subgroup, $g_2^{-1}h_1g_2$ belongs to $H$.
Hence, $h = g_2^{-1}h_1g_2h_2$ lies in $H$, and $g_1h_1g_2h_2 = g_1g_2 h \in g_1g_2H$.

Conversely,
for each element $g_1g_2 h \in g_1g_2 H$, where $h \in H$,
we have: $g_1g_2 h = (g_1\cdot e)g_2 h \in g_1H \cdot g_2H$,
since the identity element $e$ of $G$ lies in the subgroup $H$.
Hence, $g_1g_2 H \subseteq g_1H \cdot g_2 H$.

We conclude that $g_1H\cdot g_2 H = g_1g_2 H$.


Hence, $\cdot$ is a well-defined binary operation on $G/H$.

<p><blockquote><h5>Claim.</h5>
Let $H$ be a normal subgroup of a group $G$.
<ul>
<li>[Associativity:]
For all cosets $H_1, H_2, H_3$ of $H$ in $G$, we have:
$(H_1\cdot H_2)\cdot H_3 = H_1\cdot (H_2\cdot H_3)$.
%% In other words, the multiplication of left cosets is associative.

<li>[Identity:]
For all left cosets $gH$ of $H$ in $G$, we have $g H\cdot H = H\cdot gH = gH$.
%% Hence, $H$ is an identity element with respect to the multiplication of left cosets.

<li>[Inverse:]
For all $g \in G$, we have $g H \cdot g^{-1} H = H$.
%% In other words, each coset has an inverse with respect to the multiplication of left cosets.
</ul>
<p></blockquote><hr>
\begin{cor}
The set $G/H$ is a group under the multiplication $\cdot$ defined above.
Its identity element is the left coset $H$, and $(gH)^{-1} = g^{-1}H$
for all $gH \in G/H$.
\end{cor}
\quad\\
<b>Terminology.</b>
We call $G/H$ the <b>quotient group</b> of $G$ by $H$,
the quotient group of $G$ mod $H$, or simply ``$G$ mod $H$''

Note that the order of $G/H$ is equal to $[G : H]$.

<p><blockquote><h5>Example.</h5>
For all $n \in \mathbb{N}$,
The set $H = n\mathbb{Z}$ is a normal subgroup of $G = (\mathbb{Z}, +)$.
The quotient group $G/H = \mathbb{Z}/n\mathbb{Z}$ is isomorphic to $(\mathbb{Z}_n, +)$.
