<p></blockquote><hr>\quad\\
<b>Exercise:</b> If $H$ is a normal subgroup of a group $G$, and $J$ is a subgroup of $G$ containing $H$,
then $H$ is a normal subgroup of $J$.

<p><blockquote><h5>Theorem.</h5>[Third Isomorphism Theorem]
Let $G$ be a group.  Let $H, K$ be normal subgroups of $G$ such that $K$ is a subgroup of $H$.
Then, $H/K$ is a normal subgroup of $G/K$, and:
\[
(G/K)/(H/K) \cong G/H
\]
<p></blockquote><hr>
Let $\phi : G/K \ra G/H$ be the map defined by:
\[
\phi(gK) = gH, \quad \text{ for all } g \in G.
\]
If $gK = g'K$, then $g^{-1}g' \in K \subseteq H$, which implies that $\phi(gK) = gH = g'H = \phi(g'K)$.
Hence, the map $\phi$ is well-defined.

<b>Exercise:</b> $\phi$ is a surjective homomorphism.

For $gK \in G/K$, we have $\phi(gK) = gH = H$ if and only if $g \in H$,
which is equivalent to $gK \in H/K$.  Hence, $\ker \phi = H/K$,
which implies that $H/K$ is a normal subgroup of $G/H$.
It follows from the First Isomorphism theorem that:
\[
G/H \cong (G/K)/\ker \phi = (G/K)/(H/K).
\]

\quad\\
<b>Exercise:</b> Every subgroup of a cyclic group is cyclic.\\
<b>Exercise:</b> Every quotient of a cyclic group is cyclic.

<p><blockquote><h5>Example.</h5>
Let $m, n$ be natural numbers, then $m\mathbb{Z}/mn\mathbb{Z} \cong \mathbb{Z}_n$
<p></blockquote><hr>
Let $G = \mathbb{Z}$, $K = mn\mathbb{Z}$, $H = m\mathbb{Z}$.
Since $G$ is abelian, $H, K$ are normal subgroups of $G$.  Moreover, $K$ is a subgroup of $H$.
By the Third Isomorphism Theorem, we have:
\[
(\mathbb{Z}/mn\mathbb{Z})/(m\mathbb{Z}/mn\mathbb{Z}) = (G/K)/(H/K)
\cong G/H = \mathbb{Z}/m\mathbb{Z}.
\]
In particular,
\begin{multline*}
\frac{\abs{(\mathbb{Z}/mn\mathbb{Z})}}{\abs{(m\mathbb{Z}/mn\mathbb{Z})}}
=
[\mathbb{Z}/mn\mathbb{Z} : m\mathbb{Z}/mn\mathbb{Z}]
\\= \abs{(\mathbb{Z}/mn\mathbb{Z})/(m\mathbb{Z}/mn\mathbb{Z})}
 = \abs{\mathbb{Z}/m\mathbb{Z}} = \abs{\mathbb{Z}_{m}} = m.
\end{multline*}
Since $\abs{(\mathbb{Z}/mn\mathbb{Z})} = mn$, we deduce that
$m\mathbb{Z}/mn\mathbb{Z}$ is a cyclic group of order $n$, so it must be isomorphic to $\mathbb{Z}_n$.


