<p><blockquote><h5>Theorem.</h5>[Second Isomorphism Theorem]
Let $G$ be a group.  Let $N, H$ be subgroups of $G$.
If $N$ is a normal subgroup, then (i) $HN := \{hn : h \in H, n \in N\}$ is a subgroup of $G$,
(ii) $H\cap N$ is a normal subgroup of $H$,
and (iii):
\[
H/(H \cap N) \cong HN/N
\]
<p></blockquote><hr>(Note that $HN/N$ is a well-defined quotient group because by the previous exercise $N$ is a normal subgroup of $HN$.)

Proof of (i):\\
<ul>
<li>
For $h, h' \in H$, $n, n' \in N$, we want to show that $(hn)(h'n')$ lies in $HN$.
Since $N$ is a normal subgroup of $G$, $h'^{-1}nh'$ lies in $H$,
hence:
\[
hnh'n' = hh'(h'^{-1}nh')n'
\]
lies in $HN$.
<li>
Since the identity element $e$ of $G$ belongs to both $H$ and $N$,
it is clear that it lies in $HN$.
<li>
Given $hn \in HN$, its inverse in $G$ is:
\[
n^{-1}h^{-1} = h^{-1}h n^{-1}h^{-1} = h^{-1}(h n^{-1}h^{-1}),
\]
which lies in $HN$, since $N$ is a normal subgroup of $G$.
</ul>
It now follows that $HN$ is a subgroup of $G$.
%
\quad\\
Proof of (ii):
<b>Exercise.</b>\\
Proof of (iii):
Define a map $\phi : H \ra  HN/N$ as follows:
\[
\phi(h) = hN,\quad \text{ for all } h \in H.
\]
By definition of a quotient group,
multiplication in $HN/N$ is given by $hnN \cdot h'n'N = hnh'n'N$,
so:
\[
\phi(h)\phi(h') = hN\cdot h'N = hh'N = \phi(hh').
\]
Hence, $\phi$ is a group homomorphism.

The identity element of $HN/N$ is the left coset $eN = N$.
An element $h \in H$ lies in $\ker \phi$ if and only if $\phi(h) = hN = N$,
and that holds if and only if $h \in N$.  Hence, $\ker \phi = H\cap N$.

Each element of $HN/N$ is a left coset
of the form $hn N = hN = \phi(h)$, where $h \in H$.
Hence, $\phi$ is surjective.

It now follows from the First Isomorphism Theorem that:
\[H/(H\cap N) = H/\ker \phi \cong HN/N.\]



<p><blockquote><h5>Example.</h5>
Let $G = \mathbb{Z}$, $H = 6\mathbb{Z}$, $N = 4\mathbb{Z}$, with addition as the group operation.
Since $G$ is abelian, all its subgroups are normal.
We have $HN = 6\mathbb{Z} + 2\mathbb{Z} = \{6i + 4j : i, j \in \mathbb{Z}\} = gcd(6, 4)\mathbb{Z} = 2 \mathbb{Z}$.

<b>Exercise:</b>  $H \cap N = 6\mathbb{Z} \cap 4\mathbb{Z}$ is equal to $12 \mathbb{Z}$.

Applying the result of the previous example,
we see that the Second Isomorphism Theorem applied to this case says that:
\[
\mathbb{Z}_2 \cong 6\mathbb{Z}/12\mathbb{Z}
= 6\mathbb{Z}/(6\mathbb{Z} \cap 4\mathbb{Z}) = H/(H\cap N) \cong HN/N
= 2\mathbb{Z}/4\mathbb{Z} \cong \mathbb{Z}_2,
\]
which indeed holds.
