the number of factors is either always even or always odd.
<p></blockquote><hr>
<b>Exercise.</b>
One approach: There is a unique $n \times n$ matrix, with either $0$ or $1$ as its coefficients,
which sends any vector $(x_1, x_2, \ldots, x_n)$ to $(x_{\sigma(1)}, x_{\sigma(2)}, \ldots, x_{\sigma(n)})$.
Use the fact that the determinant of the matrix corresponding to a transposition is $-1$,
and that the determinant function of matrices is multiplicative.


We say that $\sigma \in S_n$ is an <b>even permutation</b>
if it is the product of an even number of transpositions.
We say that it is an <b>odd permutation</b>
if it is the product of an odd number of transpositions.

We consider the identity in $S_n$ to be an even permutation.

<p><blockquote><h5>Claim.</h5>
The even permutations of $S_n$ form a subgroup $A_n$ in $S_n$.
<p></blockquote><hr>
We call $A_n$ the <b>alternating group</b> of degree $n$.

<p><blockquote><h5>Claim.</h5>
For $n > 1$, $\abs{A_n} = n!/2$.
<p></blockquote><hr>
Let $G = S_n$.  Let $H = A_n$.
We know that $\abs{G} = n!$.
We know that each element of $G$
is either an even permutation
(i.e. product of an even number of transpositions) or an odd permutation
(i.e. product of an odd number of transpositions).
Fix a transposition $\tau_0$ in $S_n$, say $\tau_0 = (12)$.
If $\sigma \in S_n$ is an odd permutation, then by definition
$\sigma = \tau_1\tau_2\ldots\tau_l$, where each $\tau_i$ is a transposition, and $l$ is odd.
Now, observe that:
\[
\sigma = \tau_1\tau_2\ldots\tau_l = (\tau_0 \tau_0^{-1})\tau_1\tau_2\ldots\tau_l
= \tau_0 (\tau_0^{-1}\tau_1\tau_2\ldots\tau_l) \in \tau_0 A_n.
\]
Hence, each odd permutation is a product of $\tau_0$ and an even permutation.
We have:
\[
G = A_n \sqcup \tau_0 A_n.
\]
This implies that $[G : H] = 2$, hence $\abs{A_n} = \abs{H} = \abs{G}/[G : H] = n!/2$.
